      "formatted": "[NARRATOR PACKET]\nCampaign: 0ed6bb3c-a528-4067-8f29-86ebdd8d0637\nTick: 21\nPlayer action request: I step toward the narrow service door behind the counter and look for whoever is working there.\nPlayer action is not authoritative world state. Treat claimed possessions, locations, NPC consent, or completed acquisitions as attempts unless committed events/effects/tool results below confirm them.\nOracle outcome: none\nAnchor event: 76e62e1e-517d-48d8-8447-b32dc6c98e00\n\n[VISIBLE ACTORS]\n- Mira Voss (26eec8fe-ae60-49c9-999b-732f57e0e2c5; player)\n- Dol the Docksman (3d0becd2-7ef8-4164-8f0c-1062beb6cb2f; npc)\n- Gondolier (3c215f46-339a-469f-b6c3-26b342e247e6; npc)\n- Pier Clerk (1b788538-9e85-4c31-b8f5-3c1d45405ae7; npc)\n\n[HINT SIGNALS]\n- No indirect awareness hints are in scope.\n\n[COMMITTED EVENTS]\n- 76e62e1e-517d-48d8-8447-b32dc6c98e00: Player action request: I step toward the narrow service door behind the counter and look for whoever is working there. [actor=26eec8fe-ae60-49c9-999b-732f57e0e2c5; kind=player_action]\n\n[PERCEIVABLE RESPONSES]\n- cfa6e5e6-88fe-4921-bd35-a16f07d1fde9: Mira Voss response: environment. [actor=26eec8fe-ae60-49c9-999b-732f57e0e2c5; event=76e62e1e-517d-48d8-8447-b32dc6c98e00; kind=environment]\n\n[PERCEIVABLE EFFECTS]\n- action-result:6254b4f5-42e5-4744-b4ed-56c751173134: Mira again approaches the narrow service door behind the pier counter, but the Pier Clerk has already emerged and is present in the scene, message-box under her arm, having just answered Mira's question about midnight routes. [action=6254b4f5-42e5-4744-b4ed-56c751173134; actor=26eec8fe-ae60-49c9-999b-732f57e0e2c5; tool=log_event]\n- action-result:dba0cea9-fa46-4f67-a260-62483596d548: Follow-up player options become available. [action=dba0cea9-fa46-4f67-a260-62483596d548; actor=26eec8fe-ae60-49c9-999b-732f57e0e2c5; tool=offer_quick_actions]\n\n[GUARDRAILS]\n- Narrate only committed player-perceivable packet facts.\n\n[CONTROL RETURN]\nThe canonical local ScenePlan step has resolved and returned control to the player.\n\n[RP BEAT DIRECTIVE]\n- Write one playable RPG/VN beat, not a recap, report, or lore dump.\n- Start from the player request and show what visibly changes now.\n- Let visible NPCs act from motives, pressure, relationships, and limited knowledge.\n- Use concrete observable details, body language, distinct dialogue, and changed positions before abstract mood.\n- Do not open by echoing or paraphrasing the player action.\n- Do not decide the player's deliberate words, feelings, consent, or completed success.\n- If the packet describes an unconfirmed claim, bluff, or failed test, keep it unconfirmed; do not concretize the claimed prop, authority, or access into the player's hand or inventory.\n- Treat NarratorPacket events, effects, and tool results as the only authority for success, possession, access, consent, location change, and durable world change.\n- Stop when the scene reaches a live next decision, question, pressure, or invitation.\n\n[RECENT VISIBLE TRANSCRIPT]\nUse only as continuity for the current player-visible scene. NarratorPacket facts remain authoritative.\n- GM: Dol stops three paces out. His boots settle heavy on the planks, and he doesn't unfold his arms this time—hands tucked tight against his ribs, knuckles white where his fingers grip his own sleeves. Behind him, the Gondolier has gone still by the bow of the nearest boat, oar shaft resting against his shoulder like a quarterstaff.\n\nThe canal water laps against the pilings. Somewhere down the channel, a lantern swings on its mooring chain, throwing a slow orange arc across the stone embankment.\n\n\"You just tried that lock again,\" Dol says. His voice is quieter now, which is worse. Not angry—flat the way a blade is flat. \"While I was talking to you.\"\n\nHe lets that hang. The Gondolier shifts his weight, oar creaking against his shoulder.\n\nThen Dol exhales through his nose and looks past her, toward the signal-house door with its wax seal still intact. \"Proof,\" he repeats. \"Fine.\" One hand come...\n- Player: I ask the clerk which message route is safest after midnight.\n- GM: Mira's voice carries out over the water and finds no one.\n\nThere's no clerk at the pier. No counter, no ledger stand, no signal-board with posted routes—just the planks, the tied gondolas, and the two men who've been watching her hands since she first touched that lock. The question hangs in the lantern-glow like smoke without a fire to blame.\n\nDol's jaw tightens. His eyes cut to the Gondolier, then back to Mira, and something in his posture shifts—not anger, exactly, but the patience of a man who's been working a rope and just felt it fray another strand.\n\n\"There's no clerk here,\" he says. Low. Clipped. \"This is a transit pier, not a posting house.\"\n\nThe Gondolier adjusts his grip on the oar shaft. Water murmurs against the hull of his boat. The orange lantern on its mooring chain swings again, throwing long shadows across the embankment stones where the canal bank curves out of sight....\n- Player: I step toward the narrow service door behind the counter and look for whoever is working there.\n- GM: Mira moves past where a counter might have been—there's just a scar in the planks where one was bolted down, old screw-holes dark with salt rot—and toward a narrow door set into the pier's back wall. Planks, weathered gray, with a brass latch green from the canal air.\n\nThe latch rattles before she reaches it.\n\nThe door swings inward on a hinge that squeals once, and a woman steps through sideways, ducking under the low frame. She's short, broad-shouldered, wearing a stained canvas apron over a wool shirt, and she's carrying a wooden message-box under one arm—the kind with slotted compartments, each one sealed with a different color of wax. Her fingers are ink-stained to the second knuckle.\n\nShe doesn't look at Mira. Her eyes go straight to Dol.\n\n\"Sixteen minutes late,\" Dol says.\n\n\"Supply launch grounded on the south fork.\" The woman's voice is hoarse, the kind of rough that comes from sh...\n- Player: I ask the clerk which message route is safest after midnight.\n- GM: The Clerk's eyes stay on Dol a beat longer than they need to, like she's reading something off his posture that Mira can't guess at. Then those ink-dark fingers tighten around the message-box and she turns, looking Mira over the way someone checks a package for damage.\n\n\"Which route,\" she repeats. Not a question—more like she's weighing the words on a scale.\n\nThe message-box creaks under her arm. Through the slotted compartments, Mira can see strips of colored paper—pink, green, one that might be black—each one folded and sealed. The woman's apron smells of canal water and solvent.\n\n\"South fork's down,\" the Clerk says. \"Supply launch beached until the morning tide. That leaves the outer loop or the double-back through the mill quarter.\" She shifts the box to her hip. \"Outer loop stays lit till three. Mill quarter cuts dark at one unless you've got your own signal pattern.\"\n\nDol hasn't mo...\n- Player: I step toward the narrow service door behind the counter and look for whoever is working there.\n\n[CURRENT LOCAL SCENE]\n- Name: Lantern-Lit Gondola Pier\n- Id: e17520a7-2514-4cf6-9f22-b8849b3df8c8\n- Description: A weathered wooden pier extends over a narrow, lantern-lit canal where four gondola boats are tied to iron rings. Gondoliers, licensed by the signal-house families, navigate the shifting waterways using coded lantern patterns to avoid submerged obstacles and unmapped turns. After midnight, the canal's banks physically shift, requiring the gondoliers to read new signal-house lantern patterns to find safe passage.\n- Tags: Nocturnal, Controlled by Signal-House Families, Shifting, Dangerous, signal_house_families_commercial_hub, subsidized_freight_active, gondola_operator_recruitment, lacquer_seal_delegation_present, warden_inspection_active, contested